  <h1>Common Hospital Bill Misconceptions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>&ldquo;The bill is the bill — I have to pay it.&rdquo;</h2><p>The chargemaster rate is not a fixed price. No insurer pays it. Uninsured patients who simply pay the bill are paying a rate specifically designed to be discounted. Ask for itemization, apply for assistance, and negotiate.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I have insurance so I&rsquo;m protected.&rdquo;</h2><p>Insurance covers most costs but doesn&rsquo;t eliminate billing errors, balance billing from out-of-network providers, or charges exceeding your out-of-pocket maximum. Always review your EOB and compare to the hospital bill.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;Financial assistance is only for very poor people.&rdquo;</h2><p>Many hospital financial assistance programs extend to families earning 300–400% of the federal poverty level — about $90,000–$120,000 for a family of four in 2026. You may qualify even with moderate income for a large bill.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;My credit will be destroyed if I don&rsquo;t pay immediately.&rdquo;</h2><p>Medical debt under $500 was removed from credit reports in 2023. Paid medical debt is removed immediately. Unpaid medical debt must be in collections for a year before it can appear on credit reports. Negotiate before paying — don&rsquo;t rush to pay the chargemaster rate to protect your credit.</p>
  <h2>&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t negotiate if I already paid.&rdquo;</h2><p>You can still dispute billing errors after payment and request a refund for overcharges. For future bills, negotiating before paying is far easier.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-to-negotiate-hospital-bills">how to negotiate bills</a> and <a href="/guides/hospital-financial-assistance">financial assistance programs</a>.</p>
